  "name": "Myths Through Many Eyes",
  "description": "Twenty-five world myths told in their own voice, then seen through the eyes of Jung, Campbell, Frazer, the alchemists, and other interpreters. The myths come first — as living stories, not evidence for anyone's theory. Then the interpreters emerge as readers, each seeing different patterns. Thematic threads (The Descent, The Dying God, The Sacred Marriage, The Trickster) weave across cultures. The grammar inverts the usual hierarchy: the stories are primary, the theories are emergent.\n\nPUBLIC DOMAIN ILLUSTRATION REFERENCES: Greek vase paintings (6th-5th century BCE) for Greek myths. Egyptian tomb paintings and papyrus illustrations from the Book of the Dead. Mesopotamian cylinder seal impressions for Gilgamesh and Inanna. Medieval alchemical woodcuts from Rosarium Philosophorum (1550) and Atalanta Fugiens (1617). Arthur Rackham's mythology illustrations (1900s-1920s). Gustave Doré's engravings. William Blake's mythological paintings.",
  "grammar_type": "custom",
  "creator_name": "PlayfulProcess",
  "tags": ["mythology", "comparative", "jung", "campbell", "archetypes", "hero-journey", "alchemy", "depth-psychology", "world-myths"],
  "roots": ["eastern-wisdom", "mysticism", "western-philosophy"],
  "shelves": ["wisdom", "mirror"],
  "lineages": ["Shrei", "Akomolafe"],
  "worldview": "non-dual",
